<div id=3D"snopostid-89247" class=3D"sno-story-body snopostid snopostid-892=
47" data-post-id=3D"89247">
    <div id=3D"sno-story-body-content" class=3D"sno-story-body-content sno-=
no-cap">
                <tts-play-button data-id=3D"2" class=3D"tts_play_button"><t=
emplate shadowmode=3D"open"><div class=3D"wrapper"><button id=3D"tts__liste=
nt_content_2" class=3D"tts__listent_content  " type=3D"button" title=3D"Tex=
t To Audio: Click to listen post."><div classname=3D"tts_button"><svg xmlns=
=3D"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width=3D"15px" height=3D"15px" viewBox=3D"0=
 0 7 8"><polygon fill=3D"#ffffff" points=3D"0 0 0 8 7 4"></polygon></svg></=
div> <span> Listen<span></span></span></button></div></template></tts-play-=
button><p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Around a year ago, my friends d=
ecided to go to Red Robin after one of their birthday parties. I had prior =
engagements and was unable to attend, but was secretly thankful because I d=
idn=E2=80=99t want to spend a single cent of my $100 paycheck on another me=
diocre dining excursion. This moment would have gone forgotten in my mind i=
f one of my friends didn=E2=80=99t text me after the dinner, dying to share=
 the absurd tipping habits of the birthday girl.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">On a $20 meal, she tipped her server 4=
5 cents.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">45 cents? I asked my friend if their e=
xperience reflected this miserable tip, but she said the service was great =
and the food was delicious. The problem, in reality, was that the birthday =
girl =E2=80=9Cdidn=E2=80=99t have the money to tip,=E2=80=9D and didn=E2=80=
=99t show any signs of guilt for slighting that poor server. I was astounde=
d, especially because my friend works in the food industry, so she knows ho=
w hard and stressful service jobs are.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">If she didn=E2=80=99t have the money t=
o tip, why did she go out to eat in a sit-down restaurant in the first plac=
e? And why did none of my other friends say anything to her?&nbsp;</span></=
p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">What if they hold the same beliefs?&nb=
sp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">I=E2=80=99ve noticed a phenomenon rece=
ntly surrounding tipping culture: some Gen Zers believe that tipping is opt=
ional. In any video you see regarding tipping, at least </span><a href=3D"h=
ttps://www.tiktok.com/@yourtango/video/7561105948425637133?is_from_webapp=
=3D1&amp;sender_device=3Dpc&amp;web_id=3D7565214434295170591"><span style=
=3D"font-weight: 400;">one comment</span></a><span style=3D"font-weight: 40=
0;"> will be a variation of =E2=80=9CI just don=E2=80=99t get paid enough, =
I=E2=80=99d have to work two jobs,=E2=80=9D or the more aggressive, =E2=80=
=9CIt=E2=80=99s the employer=E2=80=99s job to pay their employees, not the =
customer.=E2=80=9D</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">According to a poll conducted by USA T=
oday, </span><a href=3D"https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/personalfinanc=
e/2024/06/05/tipping-gen-z-boomers-generous/73966537007/"><span style=3D"fo=
nt-weight: 400;">only 35% of Gen Z</span></a><span style=3D"font-weight: 40=
0;"> always tip when they go to a sit-down restaurant, compared to 56% of M=
illenials, 78% of Gen X=E2=80=99ers, and 86% of Baby Boomers. When compared=
 to the percentage of Gen Z workers in the restaurant industry, which has a=
 </span><a href=3D"https://blackboxintelligence.com/blog/gen-zs-flooding-in=
to-workforce-as-boomers-exit-how-can-restaurants-manage-this-shift/"><span =
style=3D"font-weight: 400;">mean of 71% across full time and part time posi=
tions</span></a><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">, the tipping statistic i=
s incompatible. Why are Gen Zers more likely to not tip their servers when =
they themselves know how grueling the service industry is, and how much ser=
vers rely on these tips as a form of income?&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The common argument against tipping is=
 that, as customers, we shouldn=E2=80=99t be responsible for supplementing =
the </span><a href=3D"https://www.paycor.com/resource-center/articles/minim=
um-wage-tipped-employees-by-state/"><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">low m=
inimum wage</span></a><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> set by the governm=
ent for service workers. While that sentiment is inherently valid, the Unit=
ed States unfortunately is not one of the </span><a href=3D"https://www.she=
rmanstravel.com/advice/save-it-20-countries-where-you-dont-need-to-leave-a-=
tip"><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">many countries that provide servers =
with a livable wage</span></a><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">, forcing a=
 dependence on tipping culture. For the average American, the extra money s=
pent on tipping can be an annoyance, especially considering that it=E2=80=
=99s not a global requirement. Nevertheless, it=E2=80=99s even worse for th=
e servers, bussers, and cooks that depend on others for their salary, which=
 fluctuates day-to-day based on the mood and opinions of their patrons. It =
isn=E2=80=99t fair for either party involved, but that=E2=80=99s how the in=
dustry is set up in our country, so it=E2=80=99s our job to help our fellow=
 workers out. As a working college student, I completely understand the pli=
ght of not having nearly enough money to go the places you want to. However=
, if you go to a restaurant where someone is waiting on you, they are provi=
ding a service </span><i><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">for you</span></=
i><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">, and deserve the respect of receiving =
adequate compensation.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Many people, including myself, grew up=
 hearing that 20% is the customary tip to leave in a restaurant and still h=
old that principle. Even when the service is unsatisfactory, a tip should s=
till be given, usually between the 10=E2=80=9315% range. You never know whe=
n someone is having a bad day, or has six other tables to wait on, so it is=
 always important to give servers the benefit of the doubt=E2=80=94they=E2=
=80=99re people too.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">However, a dilemma emerges when the ge=
nerosity of those who tip well at restaurants=E2=80=94no matter their age o=
r situation=E2=80=94is exploited through a recent implementation into the s=
ervice industry: the electronic payment model.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Many fast food chains across the count=
ry have recently added forms of electronic payment in their restaurants. </=
span><a href=3D"https://corporate.freedompay.com/resources/blogs/how-kiosks=
-are-taking-over-the-food-service-industry?=3Dpaid_search&amp;campaignid=3D=
22789656205&amp;adgroupid=3D183850632122&amp;keyword=3D&amp;device=3Dc&amp;=
utm_source=3Ddynamicgoogle&amp;utm_medium=3Dppc&amp;gad_source=3D1&amp;gad_=
campaignid=3D22789656205&amp;gbraid=3D0AAAAABJ-NQtkwVMXgqm4tG_H-FS4CiS1n&am=
p;gclid=3DCjwKCAjw6vHHBhBwEiwAq4zvA-qTT173nUBjHgODPXaw305wNHiEQwyr3Cjoz87dY=
8e7niinqu93VhoCkbMQAvD_BwE"><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Kiosks</span>=
</a><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">, whether by the register or at the f=
ront of the restaurant, provide a quick and efficient ordering service to p=
atrons, limiting the amount of mistakes on orders and eliminating the need =
for a cashier.&nbsp;</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">When purchasing food or drinks, the sc=
reen used for payment shows the option to tip with =E2=80=9Csuggested=E2=80=
=9D tipping options predetermined by the establishment. The percentages usu=
ally range from 10=E2=80=9320% in intervals, and sometimes 15=E2=80=9325% i=
f the company feels daring. Despite knowing that these workers make almost =
twice the amount per hour as compared to&nbsp; servers, customers feel obli=
gated to tip fast food workers, who are usually only handing them a cup of =
coffee.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">Daniela Canas, a freshman at Emerson, =
expressed that she =E2=80=9Calmost feels guilty not clicking 25% or somethi=
ng=E2=80=9D when at a fast food restaurant, a 5% higher percentage than wha=
t she would customarily tip at sit-in restaurants.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The guilt stretches even to millennial=
s as social sciences Professor Kara McCabe says =E2=80=9CI feel like a bad =
person if I don=E2=80=99t [tip]=E2=80=A6=E2=80=9D and believes that =E2=80=
=9Cif the tip wasn=E2=80=99t there on the screen, I wouldn=E2=80=99t [tip].=
=E2=80=9D</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">A report found that </span><a href=3D"=
https://www.kare11.com/article/news/local/kare11-sunrise/report-finds-ameri=
cans-feel-pressured-to-tip/89-ff045781-1ced-45a4-ac78-9ad26e88c0a6"><span s=
tyle=3D"font-weight: 400;">one in three</span></a><span style=3D"font-weigh=
t: 400;"> Americans feel pressured to leave a tip at a fast food restaurant=
, with over 73% reporting that they usually leave a digital tip when presen=
ted the option to. Why is it that Americans are more likely to tip a worker=
 who makes a more </span><a href=3D"https://www.bls.gov/oes/2023/may/oes353=
023.htm"><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">=E2=80=9Cliveable=E2=80=9D</span=
></a><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;"> wage as compared to a sit-in restau=
rant server who makes $3 per hour after tax?</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">The pressure felt by the glaring eyes =
of a Starbucks employee is the reason why this occurs. When you tip a serve=
r in a restaurant, most of the time, they aren=E2=80=99t staring into your =
soul implying they want a tip. But, since fast food restaurants=E2=80=94whe=
re only a counter separates the customer from the cashier, cooks, and manag=
ers=E2=80=94do not give that choice, employees might outwardly express thei=
r discontent when a customer selects =E2=80=9Cno tip=E2=80=9D, even if it=
=E2=80=99s through a disappointed sigh or the subtle drop of a smile.&nbsp;=
</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">My message to everyone who feels press=
ured to tip at fast food restaurants is to simply not tip. You are not requ=
ired to tip a service worker that makes over $15 per hour, and you shouldn=
=E2=80=99t be guilt-tripped into it. Leave a tip if you like your barista, =
or if you know the place gives you extra fries, but it is never necessary. =
They are getting paid decently well to make a quick meal or drink for you, =
and don=E2=80=99t need a tip as much as a waiter who is dealing with multip=
le tables and curating an experience for you.</span></p>
<p><span style=3D"font-weight: 400;">To those who usually don=E2=80=99t tip=
 servers well at restaurants, or even not at all, I ask you to consider giv=
ing at least 15% next time you go out to eat. Those servers are working har=
d to serve you, and that=E2=80=99s a luxury that should be respected and ap=
preciated. If you don=E2=80=99t have enough money to tip at a sit-in restau=
rant, simply don=E2=80=99t go. Try a fast food restaurant, or make a trusty=
 container of cheap ramen and eat your heart out.</span></p>
